overview: The user initiated a request to fix a pull request riddled with
  issues, including critical security flaws and broken Vercel deployments. The
  process began by systematically identifying and addressing lint errors, which
  were found to be locally resolved. A major focus was on overhauling the
  insecure authentication system, replacing a trivially forgeable cookie with
  HMAC-signed session tokens using the Web Crypto API to ensure compatibility
  with Vercel's Edge Runtime. Data handling was improved by adding robust input
  validation for API pagination and capping CSV exports to prevent memory
  exhaustion. PDF generation bugs, such as NaN values and incorrect time
  calculations, were resolved, and the "Download PDF" button was made
  functional. The NumberField component was enhanced to support null inputs, and
  Zod schema validation was extended with regex for time fields. Throughout the
  process, Vercel deployment failures were a recurring challenge, initially
  traced to a missing DATABASE_URL in the Prisma schema. This was followed by
  the discovery and resolution of a critical Next.js security vulnerability
  (CVE-2025-66478), which necessitated an upgrade of Next.js. This upgrade,
  however, introduced breaking changes in Prisma, requiring a further adjustment
  to the database configuration. Ultimately, while all code-related issues were
  resolved and the GitHub build passed, Vercel deployments continued to fail due
  to unconfigured environment variables on the Vercel platform, which the user
  was instructed to set up.
